> Imagine you would like to execute a script and it doesn't work for your,
  and like, what you will check first, why such script code doesn't work:

  - so basically, if a script is not executing, my approach would be to check
    step by step

  - first, i would check if the script has proper execution permissions

  - for example, i would verify using ls -l and if needed, i would give permission
    using chmod +x script.sh

  - next, i would check if the correct interpreter is defined, like that shebang line
    #!/bin/bash at the top of the script

  - then, i would try to execute the script using bash script.sh to see if any erros
    are displayed

  - from my experience, error messages usually help to identify the issue quickly

  - i would also check for syntax errors in the script, especially if there are missing
    brackets or incorrect commands

  - if the script depends on any external files or environment variables, i would verify
    those as well

  - additionally, i would check logs or console output to understand where it is failing

  - if needed, i would run the script in debug mode using bash -x script.sh to trace
    execution step by step

  - so basically, i check permissions, interpreter, syntax, dependencies, and logs
    identify and fix the issue
